==Latin==

===Pronunciation===
* {{la-IPA|vōx barbara}}

===Noun===
{{la-noun|[[vōx]]<3.F> [[barbarus|barbara]]<+>}}

# a [[barbarous]] word; a [[word]] which is [[said]] [[incorrect]]ly

====Declension====
{{la-ndecl|vōx<3.F> barbara<+>}}

==Latin==
===Etymology=== Literally "a voice and nothing else"
===Pronunciation=== * {{la-IPA|'vōx et praetereā nihil|vul=yes}}
===Phrase=== {{head|la|phrase|head=[[vōx]] [[et]] [[praetereā]] [[nihil]]}}
# [[nonsense]], [[claptrap]]; sounds [[without]] [[sense]]

==Latin==

===Etymology===
From {{w|Gospel of Mark|Mark}} 1:3 and {{w|Book of Isaiah|Isaiah}} 40:3 in the {{w|Vulgate}}; literally, “the voice of one crying out in the wilderness”.

===Pronunciation===
* {{la-IPA|'vōx clāmantis in dēsertō|eccl=yes}}

===Phrase===
{{head|la|phrase|head=[[vōx]] [[clamans|clāmantis]] [[in]] [[desertus|dēsertō]]}}

# [[voice in the wilderness]]; a [[prophet]] who is not listened to

{{cln|la|terms derived from the Bible}}

==Latin==
===Alternative forms=== * [[res]] audita perit, litera scripta manet: A thing heard perishes; the written letter remains. * litera scripta manet, [[verbum]] [[ut]] [[inane]] perit: The written letter remains, as the empty word perishes. * [[littera]] scripta manet, [[volat]] [[irrevocabile]] verbum: The written letter remains, the spoken word flies away, not to be recalled. * vox [[emissa]] volat, litera scripta manet: While words spoken may fly away, the written letter remains. * [[verba]] volant, scripta manent: The words fly away, the written letter remains.
===Pronunciation=== * {{la-IPA|vōx audīta perit lītera scrīpta manet|vul=yes}}
===Proverb=== {{head|la|phrase|head=[[vōx]] [[auditus|audīta]] [[pereo|perit]], [[lītera]] [[scriptus|scrīpta]] [[maneo|manet]]}}
# A heard [[voice]] [[perish]]es, but the [[written]] letter [[remain]]s.
{{C|la|Writing}}

==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|en-us-who-knows.ogg|a=US}}
* {{audio|en|En-au-who knows.ogg|a=AU}}

===Phrase===
{{head|en|phrase|head=[[who]] [[know]]s?}}

# {{n-g|A [[rhetorical question]] asked to show that the person asking it neither knows the answer nor knows who might.}}
#: ''It could be one or the other, or both. '''Who knows?'''''
#: ''Do you think I'll get married before I turn 30?'' – '''''Who knows''', you might never marry.''
# {{n-g|A rhetorical question asked to express the idea that anything is possible or that anything could happen.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Who knows?''' Maybe someday he'll finish writing his book and make lots of money selling it.}}
#: {{ux|en|Since she hasn't studied at all I don't think she'll pass the test, but '''who knows'''?}}
#: {{ux|en|Don't touch that – '''who knows''' where it's been?}}

