===Etymology 1===
{{dercat|en|gmw-pro|inh=1}}
From {{inh|en|enm|he}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hē}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hiʀ}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hiz|t=this, this one}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*ḱís|t=this}}.

Cognate with {{cog|sco|he|t=he}}, {{cog|frr|he}}, {{m|frr|hi|t=he}}, {{cog|stq|hie|t=he}}, {{cog|fy|hy|t=he}}, {{cog|nl|hij}}, {{m|nl|ie|t=he}}, {{cog|nds-de|he|t=he}}, {{cog|gmh|her|t=he}} {{cog|gmw-cfr|hä|t=he}}, {{cog|got|*𐌷𐌹𐍃|t=this}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{enPR|hē|a=UK}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈhiː/}}, {{IPA|en|/hi/|/i/|a=unstressed}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-he.ogg|a=UK}}
* {{enPR|hē|a=US}}, {{IPA|en|/hi/|[hi]|[çi]}}, {{IPA|en|/i/|a=unstressed}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-he.ogg|a=US}}
* {{rhymes|en|iː|s=1}}

====Pronoun====
{{en-pron|desc=third-person singular, masculine, nominative case|oblique|him|reflexive|himself|possessive|his}}

# {{lb|en|personal}} A [[male]] person or animal already known or implied.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1620|section=Nouell 8, The Eighth Day|title= {{w|The Decameron|The Decameron, Containing an Hundred Pleaſant Nouels: Wittily Diſcourſed, Betweene Seuen Honourable Ladies, and Three Noble Gentlemen}} |author= w:Giovanni Bocaccio|tlr= w:John Florio |publisher=Isaac Iaggard|url= https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=FEz6_FECCI0C |isbn= 9780897338677 |passage={{...}}purſued his vnneighbourly purpoſe in ſuch ſort: that '''hee''' being the ſtronger perſwader, and ſhe (belike) too credulous in beleeuing or elſe ouer-feeble in reſiſting, from priuate imparlance, they fell to action; and continued their cloſe fight a long while together, vnſeene and vvithout ſuſpition, no doubt to their equall ioy and contentment.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1886|translator=H.L. Br&aelig;kstad|author=w:Peter Christen Asbj&oslash;rnsen|title=Folk and Fairy Tales|page=77|passage="It was '''he''' we saw the tracks of down by Rausand hill."}}
#* '''July 18 2012''', Scott Tobias, AV Club ''The Dark Knight Rises''[http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-dark-knight-rises-review-batman,82624/]
#*: Though Bane’s sing-song voice gives his pronouncements a funny lilt, '''he''' doesn’t have any of the Joker’s deranged wit, and Nolan isn’t interested in undercutting his seriousness for the sake of a breezier entertainment.
#* {{seemoreCites|en}}
# {{lb|en|personal|sometimes|_|proscribed|see usage notes}} [[they|They]]; [[he or she]] {{gl|a person whose gender is unknown or irrelevant}}.
#: {{ux|en|The rulebook clearly states that "if any student is caught cheating, '''he''' will be expelled", and you were caught cheating, were you not, Anna?}}
# {{lb|en|personal|sometimes|proscribed}} [[it|It]]; an animal whose gender is unknown.
# A genderless object regarded as masculine, such as certain stars or planets (e.g. Sun, Mercury, Mars, Jupiter) or certain ships.
#: {{antonyms|en|she|it}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1770|title=A Mathematical Miscellany in Four Parts|edition=3rd|page=125
|passage=JUPITER is the largest of all the Planets, '''his''' Orbit lies between the Orbits of the ''Earth'' and ''Mars'', and at the cast Distance of 426 Millions of Miles from the Sun, '''he''' goes round '''him''' in 11 Years, 314 Days and 12 Hours; {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2019|author=Sabaton|title=Bismarck|passage=He [= the ship Bismarck] was made to rule the waves across the seven seas {{...}} }}

=====Usage notes=====
* ''He'' was traditionally used as both a [[masculine]] and a [[gender-neutral]] pronoun, but since the mid-20th century [[generic]] usage has sometimes been considered [[sexist]] and limiting.<ref>{{R:Dictionary.com}}</ref><ref>''When Words Collide: A Media Writer's Guide to Grammar and Style'' (2007, {{ISBN|0495050253}}</ref> It is deprecated by some style guides, such as ''Wadsworth''.<ref>''The Pocket Wadsworth Handbook, 2009 MLA Update Edition'' {{ISBN|1439081816}}, page 81: [A]void using the generic ''he'' or ''him'' when your subject could be either male or female. [...] '''Sexist:''' Before boarding, each passenger should make certain that he has his ticket. / '''Revised:''' Before boarding, passengers should make certain that they have their tickets.</ref> In place of generic ''he'', writers and speakers may use {{m|en|he or she}}, alternate ''he'' and {{m|en|she}} as the indefinite person, use the singular {{m|en|they}}, or rephrase sentences to use plural {{m|en|they}}.

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|person whose gender is unknown}} {{l|en|one}}, {{l|en|you}} {{q|indefinite, colloquial}}; {{l|en|he or she}}, {{l|en|he/she}}, {{l|en|they}}, {{l|en|s/he}}, ''or [[Appendix:English third-person singular pronouns|these other third-person pronouns (see "Combined forms", "Invented pronouns")]]''
* {{sense|animal whose gender is unknown}} {{l|en|it}}

