==Finnish==

===Etymology 1===
{{etymid|fi|pronoun}}
From {{inh|fi|urj-fin-pro|*hek}}, from {{inh|fi|urj-fpr-pro|*sej}}. Cognates include {{cog|se|sii}}, {{cog|myv|сынь}}. The word is inflected as plural, but there is no plural marker in the nominative, except in dialects ({{m|fi|het|id=they}}). See {{m|fi|hän}} for more details on history of usage.

====Pronunciation====
{{fi-pronunciation|a=fi-he.ogg}}

====Pronoun====
{{fi-pron}}

# {{lb|fi|personal}} [[they]] {{gloss|plural, only of people}}
# {{lb|fi|respectful}} [[#English|he]], [[she]], [[one]], (singular) [[they]] {{gloss|of a single [[human being]], like {{m|fi|hän}}}}
# [[they]] {{gloss|in indirect speech: referring to the subjects of the main clause, regardless of whether they are human beings or not, i.e. [[logophoric]] pronoun}}

=====Usage notes=====
* In standard Finnish, {{m-lite|fi||he}} is practically never omitted, despite the verb showing both the person and the number (compare the usage of {{m-lite|fi|hän}}).

=====Declension=====
* Irregular (inflectional stem {{m-lite|fi||hei-}}, as if in the plural). The [[comitative]] and [[instructive]] forms don't exist; the [[abessive]] is hardly used.
* In addition to the standard set of cases, {{m-lite|fi||he}} and other personal pronouns have a specific [[accusative]] form, {{m-lite|fi|heidät}}.

{{fi-decl-pron|1s=[[hän]]|2s=[[hänen]]|3s=[[häntä]]|4s=[[hänet]]|5s=[[hänessä]]|6s=[[hänestä]]|7s=[[häneen]]|8s=[[hänellä]]|9s=[[häneltä]]|10s=[[hänelle]]|11s=[[hänenä]]|12s=[[häneksi]]|13s=[[hänettä]]|1p='''he'''|2p=[[heidän]]|3p=[[heitä]]|4p=[[heidät]]|5p=[[heissä]]|6p=[[heistä]]|7p=[[heihin]]|8p=[[heillä]]|9p=[[heiltä]]|10p=[[heille]]|11p=[[heinä]]|12p=[[heiksi]]|13p=[[heittä]]|adv=no}}

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|dialectal}} {{l|fi|het}}
* {{sense|dialectal}} {{l|fi|hyö}}
* {{sense|colloquial}} {{l|fi|ne}}

