==Middle English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|enm|ang|hē}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*hiʀ}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*hiz||this, this one}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|enm|/heː/}}

====Pronoun====
{{head|enm|pronoun|accusative|him|or|hine|genitive|his|or|hisen|possessive determiner|his}}

# {{senseid|enm|he}} {{n-g|Third-person singular masculine pronoun:}} {{l|en|he}}
#* '''14th century''', [[w:Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer]], ''[[s:The Canterbury Tales/General Prologue|General Prologue]]'':
#*: {{quote|enm|Benynge '''he''' was, and wonder diligent|Kind '''he''' was, and very diligent}}
# {{l|en|it}}; used also of inanimate objects
# {{lb|enm|impersonal}} {{n-g|Third-person singular impersonal pronoun:}} [[one]]; [[you]]

=====Usage notes=====
In addition to referring to male humans and animals, this pronoun was used for inanimate objects belonging to the masculine grammatical gender early in Middle English.  As grammatical gender obsolesced, this pronoun continued to refer to inanimate objects.

=====Alternative forms=====
* {{alter|enm|hee|ȝe|e|hey|hi|hie|hye|heo|ho|hæ|ha|a}}

=====Descendants=====
* {{desc|en|he}}
* {{desc|sco|he}}
* {{desc|yol|hea|alts=1}}

=====See also=====
{{enm-decl-personal pronouns}}

====References====
* {{R:MED Online|he|pron|MED20189}}

