==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|thā}}, {{IPA|en|/ðeɪ/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-they.ogg|a=US}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-they.ogg|a=UK}}
* {{rhymes|en|eɪ|s=1}}

===Etymology 1===
{{etymon|en|id=pronoun|inh|enm>þei>they|tree=1}}
{{root|en|ine-pro|*só}} From {{inh|en|enm|þei}}, borrowed in the 1200s from {{der|en|non|þeir}},<ref name="AHD">{{R:American Heritage Dictionary}}</ref> plural of the demonstrative {{m|non|sá}} which acted as a plural pronoun. Displaced native {{ncog|enm|he}} from {{ncog|ang|hīe}} — which vowel changes had left indistinct from {{m|enm|he||he}} — by the 1400s,<ref name="AHD"/><ref>{{R:Etymonline}}</ref><ref>Otto Jespersen, ''Growth and Structure of the English Language''</ref> being readily incorporated alongside native words beginning with the same sound ({{m|en|the}}, {{m|en|that}}, {{m|en|this}}). Used as a singular pronoun since 1300,<ref name="AHD"/> e.g. in the 1325 ''Cursor Mundi''<!--(which uses ''[[their|þer]]'')-->.

The Norse term (whence also {{cog|is|þeir||they}}, {{cog|fo|teir|t=they}}, {{cog|da|de||they}}, {{cog|sv|de||they}}, {{cog|nn|dei||they}}) is from {{der|en|gem-pro|*þai||those}} (from {{der|en|ine-pro|*só|*to-|that}}), whence also {{cog|ang|þā||those}} (whence obsolete English {{dbt|en|tho|notext=1}}), {{cog|sco|thae}}, {{m|sco|thai}}, {{m|sco|thay||they; those}}.

The origin of the determiner {{m|en|they||the, those}} is unclear. The ''OED'', ''English Dialect Dictionary'' and ''Middle English Dictionary''<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=thei|pos=pron|id=MED45106|accessdate=2016-01-28}}</ref> define it and its Middle English predecessor {{m|enm|thei}} as a demonstrative determiner or adjective meaning "those" or "the". This could be a continuation of the use of the English pronoun {{m|en|they}}'s Old Norse etymon {{m|non|þeir}} as a demonstrative meaning "those", but the ''OED'' and ''EDD'' say it is limited to southern, especially southwestern, England, specifically outside the region of Norse contact.

====Pronoun====
{{en-pron|desc=third-person, nominative case, usually plural, sometimes singular|objective case|them|possessive|their|possessive noun|theirs|reflexive|themselves|or reflexive singular|themself}}

# {{senseid|en|third-person plural nominative}} {{lb|en|the third-person plural nominative}} A group of entities previously mentioned. {{defdate|since the 1200s}}
#: {{ux|en|Fred and Jane? '''They''' just arrived.}}
#: {{ux|en|Dogs may bark if '''they''' want to be fed.}}
#: {{ux|en|Plants wilt if '''they''' are not watered.}}
#: {{ux|en|I have a car and a truck, but '''they''' are both broken.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1620|section=Nouell 8, The Eighth Day|title= {{w|The Decameron|The Decameron, Containing an Hundred Pleaſant Nouels: Wittily Diſcourſed, Betweene Seuen Honourable Ladies, and Three Noble Gentlemen}} |author= w:Giovanni Bocaccio|tlr= w:John Florio |publisher=Isaac Iaggard|url= https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=FEz6_FECCI0C |passage={{...}}purſued his vnneighbourly purpoſe in ſuch ſort: that hee being the ſtronger perſwader, and ſhe (belike) too credulous in beleeuing or elſe ouer-feeble in reſiſting, from priuate imparlance, '''they''' fell to action; and continued their cloſe fight a long while together, vnſeene and vvithout ſuſpition, no doubt to their equall ioy and contentment.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|title=Iguana Invasion!: Exotic Pets Gone Wild in Florida|page=9|isbn=1561644684
|passage=There is no reason to be scared of iguanas. '''They''' do not attack humans.}}
# {{senseid|en|third-person singular nominative}} {{lb|en|the third-person singular nominative|occasionally|proscribed}} A single person, previously mentioned, but typically not if previously named and identified as male or female, especially if of unknown, irrelevant or (since 21st century) [[non-binary]] [[gender]]. Now increasingly used for an unnamed person even if the gender of the person is identified. {{defdate|since the 1300s}}
#: {{ux|en|Somebody requested a seat at Friday's performance but didn't say if '''they''' preferred the balcony or the floor.}}
#: {{ux|en|If someone enters the restricted area, '''they''' are required to present identification.}}
#: {{ux|en|One of the boys tripped over, and '''they''' hit their head on the door.}}
#* {{RQ:King James Version|Deuteronomy|17|5|passage=Then shalt thou bring forth that man, or that woman (which haue committed that wicked thing) vnto thy gates, euen that man, or that woman, and shalt stone '''them''' with stones till '''they''' die.}}
#* {{quote-book
|en
| year = 1997
| author = w:J. K. Rowling
| chapter = 10
| title = {{w|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone}} <!-- USA edition: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone -->
| location = (quoted edition: London <!-- New York -->
| publisher=Bloomsbury, 2000 <!-- Arthur A Levine, imprint of Scholastic, 1999 -->
| isbn = 0-7475-4955-9 <!-- 0-590-35342-X -->
| page = 187) <!-- 172 -->
| passage = Someone knocked into Harry as '''they''' hurried past him. It was Hermione.
}}
